Economic Freedom Fighters Julius Malema on Friday opened a case against Finance Minister Malusi Gigaba who he alleges is at the centre of corrupt activities at parastatal Transnet. we bought 1 unit of a locomotive for R42m. No country in the world has ever bought a locomotive for that much, not even in rich ones, Said Malema on Friday while addressing EFF followers.Case Number: CAS 384/6/2017 &#8211; #TransnetCorruption&mdash; EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) June 9, 2017&nbsp;The EFF indicated the cases they had opened ranged from charges of fraud, corruption, racketeering and money laundering.CIC @Julius_S_Malema and EFF Officials laying charges against Gigaba and others at Joburg Central Police Station #TransnetCorruption pic.twitter.com/gln1wn8lpq&mdash; EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) June 9, 2017&nbsp;The EFF made public their intentions to open a case against Gigaba during a press conference yesterday. During the press conference Malema claimed that they have evidence and information that pointed at corruption between parastatal&#8217;s and private individuals.Meanwhile they also announced that they had also opened a case against President Jacob Zuma and the Gupta family. We have opened so many cases including against Zuma and to this day he has not been charged.Even today we know police won&#8217;t do anything, Malema said.However they promise to solicit further help from foreign governments. &#8230;We will also write to the USA, Canada and Chinese government as their companies are involved in this corruption of R17b. Malema said Gigaba and the ANC must know that once USA companies are involved, including the dollar, you have invited the FBI of USA. He addedEFF CIC @Julius_S_Malema and the leadership now at Joburg Central Police Station to lay charges against Gigaba et.al. #TransnetCorruption pic.twitter.com/3mrgsp3KEF&mdash; EFF Official Account (@EFFSouthAfrica) June 9, 2017-TNA Reporter &nbsp;&nbsp;